#Text=Waves of arrests in Turkey on suspicion of involvement in ' Ergenekon ' organization
#Text=Sunday , January 11 , 2009
#Text=Turkish police arrested two colonels and two lieutenants Saturday as part of a wide-reaching probe into a suspected coup plot .
#Text=The arrests are the latest related to an alleged clandestine neonationalist organization referred to as " Ergenekon " .

column1: #Text=The Ergenekon case has had adverse effects on financial markets in Turkey , a candidate for the European Union .

#Text=Turkey 's state-run news service , Anatolian News , reported that the four Turkish army officers were arrested in Istanbul for alleged ties to a right-wing group suspected of conspiring to overthrow the AK Party government .
#Text=40 people were detained on Wednesday , including three retired army generals .
#Text=Recep Tayyip Erdoğan
#Text=Image : World Economic Forum .
#Text=Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan and General Ilker Basbug , Chief of the General Staff of the Turkish Armed Forces , held crisis talks on Thursday to discuss the recent waves of arrests .
#Text=General Basbug met with the prime minister after a six-hour meeting with military commanders , including members of the Gendarmerie , Turkish Air Force , and Army .
#Text=After his meeting with the prime minister , General Basbug met with President Abdullah Gul .
#Text=President Abdullah Gul met with Besir Atalay , Turkey 's interior minister .
#Text=The talks between Erdogan and Basbug prompted a spate of selling on the Istanbul Stock Exchange , which fell by six percent on Thursday .
#Text=TUSIAD , the main business association in Turkey , voiced its hope that investigators respect the legal rights of the suspects .
#Text=Turkish media also reported Saturday that law enforcement officials found ammunition and grenades buried near Golbasi lake outside Ankara , supposedly related to the Ergenekon organization .
#Text=According to the Turkish media reports , police found a drawing in the home of former police chief Ibrahim Sahin , which led them to the site .
#Text=Ibrahim Sahin was among the 40 individuals arrested Wednesday .
#Text=This is a regime change , like in the Khomeini and Hitler eras .
#Text=— Deniz Baykal , leader of the Republican People 's Party
#Text=Deniz Baykal , who heads Turkey 's secular chief opposition party the Republican People 's Party , was critical of the arrests made by police under the AK Party government .
#Text=" We are witnessing a confrontation against the Republic 's core values .

column1: #Text=Members of the Turkish state bureaucracy , military , and judicial system make up the country 's secularist establishment .
#Text=According to Reuters , this secularist establishment states that the arrests carried out by the AK Party are retaliatory , in response to a 2008 court case .
#Text=The court case attempted to ban the AK Party , which has roots in political Islam , for anti-secular activities .
#Text=The AK Party has denied these claims .
#Text=The risk of a reaction by the military is growing as the Ergenekon probe is turning into a test of strength between the AKP and secularist circles .
#Text=— Wolfango Piccoli , Eurasia Group

#Text=" The risk of a reaction by the military is growing as the Ergenekon probe is turning into a test of strength between the AKP and secularist circles , " said analyst Wolfango Piccoli of the Eurasia Group in a statement published in the Financial Times .
#Text=The investigation by the government began in June 2007 , when officials discovered a cache of arms in Istanbul in the home of a retired military officer .
#Text=According to The Guardian , in total approximately 200 people have been arrested in relation to the investigation .
#Text=86 individuals have been indicted since the investigation started , including many officials from the military and two retired four-star generals .
#Text=In addition to military officials , the investigation has focused on journalists , writers , politicians and leaders of gangs .
#Text=The murder of journalist Hrant Dink is sometimes cited as possibly linked to the Ergenekon case .
#Text=The indictments allege involvement in plans to increase instability in the country through political assassinations .

#Text=Hürriyet reported that the Ergenekon investigation has faced criticism in the past for detaining suspects for extended periods of time in prison without charges , and for its reliance on insubstantial evidence .
#Text=In the past 50 years , the country 's military has intervened to topple four governments in Turkey .
